Talen Energy Corporation this week announced it has sold its 960MW Cumulus =
data center campus in Pennsylvania to a =E2=80=98major cloud service provid=
er=E2=80=99 =E2=80=93 listed as Amazon in a Talen investor presentation [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/e0478e82-ce0b-4326-90df-4362c12be960?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Welcome to the Age of Miracles [ https://substack.com/redirect/f94e74e0-47d=
6-4293-88a1-50f5522c4959?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Amazon!=20
Data Center Dynamics reported that the bookseller has acquired a 960MW data=
 center at a nuclear power station in my home commonwealth of Pennsylvania =
for $650 million. =20
While it=E2=80=99s not new nuclear, this is big news for a few reasons.=20
As Mark Nelson highlights [ https://substack.com/redirect/b111b942-c0e3-473=
5-aa95-d757d47141af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], it=E2=80=99s Amazon=E2=80=99s first foray into nuclear. The =
company is the last of the hyperscalers to admit that nuclear is a good, cl=
ean energy source to power their energy hungry data centers.=20
Those companies =E2=80=94 Amazon, Google, Meta, and Microsoft =E2=80=94 con=
sume over 22 gigawatts of electricity in the US each year, and S&P conserva=
tively estimates that number will grow to 33GW by in the next few years [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/afd04910-abd7-4e71-b1fe-f65aacf65191?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. In order to go=
 clean and maintain ESG ratings, they=E2=80=99ve contracted for 40GW of ren=
ewable power (the quoted capacity is higher than the 22GW need for a bunch =
of reasons, including intermittency). For context, the US has only 95GW of =
nuclear capacity.=20
Data centers may represent a huge catalyst for nuclear energy. Utilities ar=
e pretty terrible buyers for nuclear reactors, but hyperscalers are faster-=
moving and more economically motivated. Their soaring hunger for electricit=
y may kickstart the process of building more reactors and driving them down=
 the learning curve [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a7c0783-f83f-4e01-aea4=
-9752739a7756?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ].
And not a moment too soon=E2=80=A6 the Russians and Chinese are discussing =
a partnership to build a nuclear reactor on the Moon by 2035 [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/cfa2b17e-f272-4e9f-a950-d65d8d16a559?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Look, I=E2=80=99m all for a little international competition, but if anyone=
=E2=80=99s Putin the first nuclear reactor on the Moon, I want it to be the=
 US of A.=20
(2) Gigascale Hydrocarbon Synthesis: Casey Handmer, Terraform Industries [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/d05a6ddb-7364-40a1-9769-2f238d9836c0?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
I love all clean, cheap energy sources, and solar=E2=80=99s ride down the l=
earning curve has been a thing of beauty.=20
It=E2=80=99s that learning curve that convinced Not Boring favorite Casey H=
andmer to start Terraform Industries [ https://substack.com/redirect/62ade8=
34-c400-4727-be86-566431bf5773?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which is =E2=80=9Cscaling technology to produce c=
heap natural gas with sunlight and air.=E2=80=9D=20
On the second episode of First Principles, Christian Keil [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/00f73717-0302-4a0f-9b91-5f9f6fa664eb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] digs in on the details with C=
asey. They cover everything why hydrocarbons are good, how to make syntheti=
c methane (and eventually synthetic fuels), the Sabatier Reaction, and why =
cheap solar energy makes it all possible.=20
My favorite part about Terraform is that if it=E2=80=99s successful, it wil=
l create even more demand for solar, driving down the price of one of its k=
ey inputs even further, and making solar a more abundant energy source for =
the world. Plus, it takes advantage of solar=E2=80=99s advantages without o=
verloading the grid. Smart.=20
(3) [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3c803ee-5a6b-46e9-afba-6fe00defa38b?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]  [ http=
