 northern Minnesota may be biggest ever in North America [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/c3c803ee-5a6b-46e9-afb=
a-6fe00defa38b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jonah Kaplan for CBS News
According to Abraham-James, the helium concentration was measured at 12.4%,=
 which is higher than forecasted and roughly 30 times the industry standard=
 for commercial helium."12.4% is just a dream. It's perfect," he said.
OK OK fine we=E2=80=99re getting really good at producing cheap, clean ener=
gy, but we can=E2=80=99t continue to grow because we=E2=80=99ll run out of =
resources, right? Wrong.=20
We just keep finding more of the things we need. Like the 2.34 billion metr=
ic tons of rare earth minerals found southwest of Wheatland, Wyoming [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/0f1e5586-11c0-4bae-ad2a-779d16d3f92a?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] last month. Or the=
 enormous lithium deposits discovered in California=E2=80=99s Salton Sea [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/3c3c2975-27aa-492d-b967-0967dc4548b2?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
And now, helium in Minnesota. This week, Pulsar Helium announced the discov=
ery of what might be the largest helium deposits ever discovered in North A=
merica.=20
Helium is best-known for its pivotal role in making balloons float and voic=
es squeak, but it=E2=80=99s also a fantastic coolant, something that=E2=80=
=99s going to get more important as we build more big, hot things.=20
Helium is used in MRI machines (which might help beat cancer [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/39312d22-d2b3-4274-93d1-4d43cb3eaca2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), semiconductor manufactur=
ing, and fusion reactors. If things go well in the world, we=E2=80=99re goi=
ng to need a lot more helium, and now we have billions of standard cubic me=
ters of the good good 12.4% stuff.=20
The combination of human ingenuity, capitalism, and America=E2=80=99s bless=
ed natural resources keeps winning.=20
(4) User-Owned Foundation Models [ https://substack.com/redirect/b4ea4ff0-9=
0d6-4df6-b290-1ba1559388f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Foundation models tend towards monopolies, as they require huge upfront inv=
estments in the form of data and compute. It=E2=80=99s tempting to resign o=
urselves to the easy option: do the best we can with hand-me-down, open sou=
rce models that are a few generations behind, the leftovers from large AI c=
ompanies. But we shouldn=E2=80=99t settle for being a few generations behin=
d and only eating leftovers! We as users should create our own best model =
=E2=80=94 we have the data and compute to make it possible.
Anna Kazlauskas [ https://substack.com/redirect/e7eed097-ebb4-4ec4-807c-b63=
531f606a8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], the founder of our portfolio company Vana [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/1bbb192b-3dcc-4626-8eb3-70738cf4a7f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], has been building in crypto and AI sinc=
e long before any token that even smells like AI went to infinity. The cryp=
to x AI narrative is running years ahead of practical implementation, and m=
ost of those tokens will crash and burn, but there=E2=80=99s a path.=20
Anna paints a compelling vision for user-owned foundation models: =E2=80=9C=
Users who contribute to the model would collectively own and govern it. The=
y could get paid when the model is used, or even paid proportionally to how=
 much their data improved the model.=E2=80=9D
And she brings the facts. Models need a lot of two things to work: data and=
 compute. Collectively, people have a ton of data and a ton of compute.=20
Data: 453 trillion words locked as our private data across big platforms (w=
ith an order of magnitude more as we start recording more of our lives).
Compute: Ethereum miners ran 16.4 million GPUs when the chain was proof of =
work, many multiples of the amount used to train GPT-4. When the incentives=
 are right, people can pool vast resources.=20
There are challenges, of course. Not all data is high quality, and models p=
erform better with high quality data. And distributed GPUs aren=E2=80=99t o=
ptimized for training the way a purpose-built data center is.=20
But with the battle over closed versus open AI raging on [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/6335947f-428d-43b3-8b4=
b-307cc6442a7a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], with companies like Google sh=
owing that they want to put their own spin on their models=E2=80=99 outputs=
, and with AI becoming more powerful every week, it=E2=80=99s useful to thi=
nk about alternatives that would give people more control and ownership.=20
* Speaking of AI getting better, you should really check out Anthropic=E2=
=80=99s Claude 3 [ https://substack.com/redirect/a02263dd-2471-4f8d-a556-e7=
d97b76758c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. It=E2=80=99s winning on benchmarks, but it also just feels smarter. I=
t=E2=80=99s my favorite thought partner for now, until next week when someo=
ne else comes out with something better. What a time to be alive.=20
(5) Delhi Painter Gets Hands Back As Organ Donation Meets Surgical Excellen=
ce [ https://substack.com/redirect/ec4e78ce-bdea-434f-a4ed-39b2f84e738e?j=
